<div id="review_3087583" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3087583" />
    <a title="Robert Page" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/80141-robert-page"><img alt="Robert Page" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1178662654p2/80141.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3087583?book_show_action=true">Jul 14, 2007</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Robert Page" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Robert Page" href="/user/show/80141-robert-page">Robert Page</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="did not like it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">did not like it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>


          <div><span class="uitext greyText">Recommends it for: </span>
           <span class="uitext reviewText">Anyone who wants to get 100 pages in and give up in despair</span></div>

        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3087583" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer9454890694296010079">Bah. Many people won&apos;t find this review helpful. I do care about that, but not enough to change my review, because I feel it encompasses my feelings for this book quite fully. Here it is:<br/><br/>I had to choose between continuing to read ECGTB or staring at the back of the airplane seat in front of me. <br/><br/>I chose the back of the seat.<br/><br/>Repeatedly.<br/><br/>I&apos;d read a section, and think to myself &quot;This is shit!&quot; and put it down to stare at the seat in front of me. Then I would think to myself &quot;Come on. You&apos;re on a plan</span>
  <span id="freeText9454890694296010079" style="display:none">Bah. Many people won't find this review helpful. I do care about that, but not enough to change my review, because I feel it encompasses my feelings for this book quite fully. Here it is:<br /><br />I had to choose between continuing to read ECGTB or staring at the back of the airplane seat in front of me. <br /><br />I chose the back of the seat.<br /><br />Repeatedly.<br /><br />I'd read a section, and think to myself "This is shit!" and put it down to stare at the seat in front of me. Then I would think to myself "Come on. You're on a plane, and you have a book to read--a book by a renowned author. Just read the damn thing!" <br /><br />But I couldn't!<br /><br />So I would stare at the seatback for awhile, then pick up the book again and try to read it. It didn't work. So I would put the book down again and stare. <br /><br />Rinse and repeat. Ugh!<br /><br />I don't hate this book, but I found it to be self-indulgent drivel. I couldn't finish it, and I can't remember the last book I could say that about.<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /></span>
